Introduction

This notebook compares across all options for weight computation which are available in the epiregulon package. As a ground truth the data simulated by scMultiSim package is used.

Highlights

  • GRN is composed of 5000 target genes and 500 transcription factors
  • 9 cell clusters
  • normalization of the count data
  • using moving cutoffs in the workflows with regulon pruning

GRN preparation

set.seed(10101)
# number of target genes
n_target <- 5e3
# number of transcription factors
n_tf <- 500
# target numbers
n_targets <- rep(0, n_tf)
# minimum number of target genes per transcription factor should be 3
while(any(n_targets < 3))
    n_targets[n_targets < 3] <- rpois(sum(n_targets < 3), exp(runif(sum(n_targets < 3))*5))
n_targets[n_targets > n_target] = n_target
# set number of transcription factors per target gene
n_tfs_per_target <- sample(1:n_target, sum(n_targets)-n_target, replace  =TRUE)
# ensure at least one transcription factor per target gene
n_tfs_per_target <- c(n_tfs_per_target, 1:n_target)
n_tfs_per_target <- table(n_tfs_per_target)
reg_matrix <- matrix(0, ncol = n_tf, nrow = n_target, dimnames = list(1:n_target, (n_target+1):(n_target+n_tf)))
connected_targets <- c()
for (i in 1:ncol(reg_matrix)){
    # account for possible repeated target genes at the last step by using min function
    tgs <- sample(setdiff(1:n_target, connected_targets), min(n_targets[i], length(setdiff(1:n_target, connected_targets))))
    reg_matrix[tgs,i] <- 1
    # find exhausted targets
    connected_targets <- which(rowSums(reg_matrix)==n_tfs_per_target)
}

GRN <- reshape2::melt(reg_matrix)
GRN <- GRN[GRN[,3]==1, 1:2]
colnames(GRN) <- c("regulated.gene", "regulator.gene")
GRN$regulator.effect <- runif(nrow(GRN), min=1, max =5)

# prepare phylogenetic tree
library(ape)
phyla <- fork.tree <- stree(2)
phyla <- bind.tree(phyla, fork.tree, 1)
phyla <- bind.tree(phyla, phyla, 1)
phyla <- bind.tree(phyla, phyla, 1)
phyla <- compute.brlen(phyla, c(3, 2, 4, 1, 1, 2, 2, 2, 2, 4, 8, 5, 3, 2, 2, 5))
plot(phyla)

# prepare simulation options
options_ = list(
    rand.seed = 0,
    GRN = GRN,
    num.cells = 5000, # number of cells
    num.cifs = 500,
    tree = phyla, # tree with 9 clusters
    intrinsic.noise = 0.9,
    giv.prob = 0.05,
    augmented.transcr = NULL, # custom parameter
    atac.effect = 0.5, # effect of regulatory element availability on k_on parameter
    diff.cif.fraction = 0.8, # fraction of CIFs related to the cell development 
    discrete.cif = TRUE, # use discrete mode
    discrete.min.pop.size = 300)
library(scMultiSim)
sim_res <- sim_true_counts(options_)

# add noise to gene expression and ATAC-seq data
set.seed(11000)
add_expr_noise(sim_res)
# pointers to objects starting with . will disappear during conversion from environment to list
.grn <- sim_res$.grn
sim_res <- as.list(sim_res)
sim_res$.grn <- .grn 
dimnames(sim_res$counts_obs) <- dimnames(sim_res$counts)
saveRDS(sim_res, "/gstore/scratch/u/wlodarct/sim_res.rds")
#Sys.setenv("R_MAX_VSIZE" = 30 * 2^30)
sim_res <- readRDS("/gstore/scratch/u/wlodarct/sim_res.rds")
library(epiregulon.benchmark)
library(scMultiSim)
tfs <- NULL
counts_removal_old <- NULL
tfs <- unique(options_$GRN[,2])
# get gene expression data after removal of each transcription factor (one by one) 
# analysed using 900Gb of RAM
# set in .Renviron R_MAX_VSIZE = "800Gb"
counts_removal <- removeTF(sim_res, BPPARAM = BiocParallel::MulticoreParam(),
                                  batch_size = 20, sim_options = options_,
                           tfs = tfs)

# calculate the effect of transcription factor by subtracting the gene expression matrix after removal
# from the basic dataset and summing transcription change across all the target genes
true_ranks_matrix <- calculateTrueActivityRanks(basic_sim_res = sim_res,
                                                counts_removal = counts_removal,
                                                sim_options = options_)

transcription_difference_matrix <- calculateTrueActivityRanks(basic_sim_res = sim_res,
                                                    counts_removal = counts_removal,
                                                    sim_options = options_,
                                                    transcription_effect = TRUE)

Effect of the number of target genes

# calculate ranking mismatch score for true counts analysed using wilcoxon method in addWeights
ranking_accuracy_wilcoxon <- assessActivityAccuracy(activities_obs = score_matrices_true_counts$wilcoxon, true_ranks_matrix = true_ranks_matrix)

# determine number of target genes per tf
target_number <- split(options_$GRN,options_$GRN$regulator.gene) |> 
    lapply(nrow) |> 
    {function(x) unlist(x)}()
df <- data.frame(interchange_number = ranking_accuracy_wilcoxon$interchange_number, 
                 target_number = target_number[names(ranking_accuracy_wilcoxon$interchange_number)])

plot(df$interchange_number~df$target_number, main = "Effect of regulon size on the accuracy of prediction of\ntranscription factor activity", xlab = "Number of target genes per transcription factor", ylab = "Rankings mismatch score", pch = 16, cex = 0.5)

Effect of the network pruning

Now letâ€™s check the methodsâ€™ performance by adding false connections and playing around with different cutoff values for the output from pruneRegulon function. By default we use moving cutoffs for binarization of peak and gene expression data. Moreover, only normalized true counts and true peak data are analysed. We start with pruning the true regulon (without adding any false connections).

Pruning unconataminated regulon

Fixed cutoffs for pruning

Manipulating data sparsity

We can modify parameters which generate technical noise in our data. We will set non-default values to the following parameters - alpha_mean which is the the mean of the normal distribution used to sample efficiency with transcripts are captured from the library - alpha_sd which is the standard deviation of the above distribution, i.e.Â determined how much cells differ from each other - alpha_gene_meea which is the mean of the normal distribution from which gene-specific capture effciency will be sampled - alpha_gene_sd which is the standard deviation for the above distribution - depth_mean which is the the mean of the normal distribution used to sample library sequencing depth - depth_sd which is the standard deviation for the above distribution - observation_prob which corresponds to the probability that ATACseq count will be included in the final dataset - sd_frac which controls for the size of the noise relative to the signal of ATACseq.

Sparsity lesser than default
